{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:35:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:35:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17615"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17615"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.49,0.1,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79493"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10329"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17615"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6663"},{"type":"tags","id":"6667"},{"type":"tags","id":"7177"},{"type":"tags","id":"7304"},{"type":"tags","id":"11264"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26010"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79493"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the course of the vertebral arteries in the neck?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ascend through transverse foramina C7 to C2","Ascend through transverse foramina C6 to C1","Ascend through intervertebral foramina","Ascend anterior to cervical vertebrae","Pass between transverse processes without entering foramina"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral arteries (image) ascend through the transverse foramina of cervical vertebrae C6 to C1\u003C/strong\u003E. They arise from the subclavian arteries and typically enter at the level of C6, travelling superiorly through each successive transverse foramen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending through transverse foramina C7 to C2\u003C/strong\u003E - The transverse foramina of C7 do not typically contain the vertebral arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending through intervertebral foramina\u003C/strong\u003E - These foramina contain spinal nerve roots, not the vertebral arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending anterior to cervical vertebrae\u003C/strong\u003E - This would leave the arteries vulnerable to injury\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPass between transverse processes without entering foramina\u003C/strong\u003E - The arteries are protected within the bony transverse foramina\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter exiting C1, the vertebral arteries course posteriorly around the lateral masses of the atlas before entering the foramen magnum. They then join to form the basilar artery at the pontomedullary junction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vertebral arteries arise from the subclavian arteries, they then ascend through the transverse foramina of cervical vertebrae C6 to C1.","The vertebral arteries enter the skull through the foramen magnum and join to form the basilar artery.","The vertebral arteries course posteriorly around the lateral masses of the atlas (C1) before entering the foramen magnum."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cVertebral Artery\u201d by Mikael H\u00e4ggstr\u00f6m is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Vertebral_artery.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17615"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21378"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21378"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RpYj5uWV7qoVwKcFzYPMF6LAftQcBd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RpYj5uWV7qoVwKcFzYPMF6LAftQcBd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":922}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T20:13:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T20:13:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10329"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79493"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://ap